<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910306-0152</DOCNO><DOCID>910306-0152.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Denison Mines Ltd.:   Cuts in Uranium Production   And Staff Are Due to Costs</HL><DATE>03/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   DEN.A FTX J.TER</CO><IN>NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)DIVERSIFIED MINING (MNG)</IN><LP>   Denison Mines Ltd., Toronto, said it plans to cut uraniumproduction in half and reduce by one-third the work force atits mine in Elliot Lake, Ontario, because of high productioncosts.   Denison said it will obtain uranium from its joint venturewith a unit of Freeport-McMoRan Inc. of New Orleans tofulfill contract obligations to Tokyo Electric Power Co., oneof Denison's major customers.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We can't deliver the (Tokyo Electric) contract fromElliot Lake because the costs are too high,&quot; said WilliamJames, Denison's president and chief executive officer.   Mr. James wouldn't elaborate, but analysts estimate itcosts Denison as much as $40 (U.S.) to produce a pound ofuranium at Elliot Lake. This figure compares with a spotmarket price for uranium of around $10 a pound.   Denison said annual uranium production at Elliot Lake willbe reduced from 2.7 million pounds, to 1.4 million pounds.</TEXT></DOC>